105
00:05:41,812 --> 00:05:43,453
That's different from Dungeons and Dragons,

106
00:05:43,453 --> 00:05:45,734
where most mechanics revolve around combat,

107
00:05:45,734 --> 00:05:47,895
and the job of weaving a narrative around them

108
00:05:47,895 --> 00:05:51,638
is typically done outside of the core system of the game.

109
00:05:51,638 --> 00:05:56,361
Alternatively, indie RPGs often lean into this fiction.

110
00:05:56,361 --> 00:05:58,422
So generally, they're not about winning or losing,

111
00:05:58,422 --> 00:06:01,744
though of course, every rule has exceptions.

112
00:06:01,744 --> 00:06:03,465
In a challenge-based game like D&D,

113
00:06:03,465 --> 00:06:05,387
there kind of needs to be a loss condition

114
00:06:05,387 --> 00:06:08,929
so that the challenges that form the focus of play

115
00:06:08,929 --> 00:06:09,770
are meaningful.

116
00:06:10,843 --> 00:06:13,904
But in most indie RPGs, standing up and failing a challenge

117
00:06:13,904 --> 00:06:16,666
might be just as impactful in a character's narrative arc

118
00:06:16,666 --> 00:06:18,367
as success would be, and therefore

119
00:06:18,367 --> 00:06:19,847
