This game is all about setting players as characters

254
00:13:44,020 --> 00:13:47,082
in a complicated, interwoven caper

255
00:13:47,082 --> 00:13:49,344
where everything goes to shit very quickly.

256
00:13:49,344 --> 00:13:53,288
The tagline is ordinary people with powerful ambition

257
00:13:53,288 --> 00:13:55,189
and very poor impulse control.

258
00:13:55,189 --> 00:13:57,591
This is a fantastic game.

259
00:13:58,472 --> 00:14:00,373
The game begins by setting up relationships

260
00:14:00,373 --> 00:14:05,356
between characters using cards in its newest iteration,

261
00:14:05,356 --> 00:14:07,197
or dice in the classic form,

262
00:14:07,197 --> 00:14:09,018
along with other plot elements

263
00:14:09,018 --> 00:14:10,719
that will be part of the story.

264
00:14:10,719 --> 00:14:14,001
So, glossing over the overall structure,

265
00:14:14,001 --> 00:14:16,463
but essentially, in each turn,

266
00:14:16,463 --> 00:14:19,805
a player will set a scene with some subset

267
00:14:19,805 --> 00:14:21,486
of the other players at the table

268
00:14:21,486 --> 00:14:23,607
to develop on some thorny situation

269
00:14:23,607 --> 00:14:25,188
that they were originally put in.

270
00:14:25,188 --> 00:14:26,529
Maybe they need someone beaten up.

271
00:14:27,029 --> 00:14:30,610
Maybe their cousin is a bookie and they can help them out.

272
00:14:30,610 --> 00:14:31,151
You get it.

273
00:14:31,151 --> 00:14:35,112
As the scene reaches a climactic point,

274
00:14:35,112 --> 00:14:37,713
the players at the table not in the scene

275
00:14:37,713 --> 00:14:38,994
determine if things go well

276
00:14:38,994 --> 00:14:43,415
or if indeed they go very poorly for the active players.

277
00:14:43,415 --> 00:14:46,296
The active players will then use that prompt

278
00:14:46,296 --> 00:14:48,397
to resolve the tension of the scene.

279
00:14:52,948 --> 00:14:59,978
So, from the example of fiasco, I think that we can see that there actually wasn't a whole

280
00:14:59,978 --> 00:15:05,506
lot about the narrative authority being vested in a single party that was fundamental to

281
00:15:05,506 --> 00:15:05,907
the form.

282
00:15:07,387 --> 00:15:11,149
In fiasco, the role of the GM is spread dynamically

283
00:15:11,149 --> 00:15:12,730
among everyone at the table.

284
00:15:12,730 --> 00:15:14,471
Depending on how you look at it,

285
00:15:14,471 --> 00:15:17,974
you might say that this means that there are either no GMs,

286
00:15:17,974 --> 00:15:19,795
leading to the term GM-less,

287
00:15:19,795 --> 00:15:23,277
or perhaps that everyone is a GM in this case,

288
00:15:23,277 --> 00:15:25,399
giving us the term GM-full,

289
00:15:25,399 --> 00:15:28,181
and the paradox being that both of these terms

290
00:15:28,181 --> 00:15:29,582
end up meaning very similar things.

291
00:15:29,582 --> 00:15:35,566
So with fiasco, this distribution of narrative authority

292
00:15:35,566 --> 00:15:36,466
is done mechanically.

293
00:15:37,660 --> 00:15:40,905
But this is by no means the only way

294
00:15:40,905 --> 00:15:43,428
of splitting narrative authority and how it can be handled.

295
00:15:43,428 --> 00:15:48,595
So another great example of this is the game 1,001 Nights

296
00:15:48,595 --> 00:15:50,998
by McGay Baker, where players each

297
00:15:50,998 --> 00:15:54,402
improvised tales in the style of Scheherazade's 1,001 Arabian

298
00:15:54,402 --> 00:15:54,723
Nights.

299
00:15:55,864 --> 00:15:58,806
So here, gameplay is split between the present day,

300
00:15:58,806 --> 00:16:01,228
you are members of an Arabian court,

301
00:16:01,228 --> 00:16:04,251
going about your daily lives, and its intrigues,

302
00:16:04,251 --> 00:16:08,654
and the various stories that you use to connect with others.

303
00:16:08,654 --> 00:16:13,978
So when telling a story, usually to expand on juicy points

304
00:16:13,978 --> 00:16:17,681
that came up in court, the players will start to improvise

305
00:16:17,681 --> 00:16:19,162
in the style of A Thousand and One Nights.

306
00:16:20,063 --> 00:16:23,245
and when they need to introduce a totally new character for their story,

307
00:16:23,245 --> 00:16:27,267
they'll recruit another court character to play the role.

308
00:16:27,267 --> 00:16:33,711
Then this recruited player has narrative authority over that part of the story.

309
00:16:33,711 --> 00:16:38,614
So in A Thousand and One Nights, narrative control flows from the fiction itself

310
00:16:38,614 --> 00:16:42,896
rather than being heavily mechanized, which is a nice distinction between it and fiasco.

311
00:16:47,638 --> 00:16:53,866
Another way in which games have sought to do away with the role of GM has been to carve

312
00:16:53,866 --> 00:16:58,052
it up and distribute discrete chunks of it to players explicitly.

313
00:16:58,052 --> 00:17:03,379
So two games that split narrative authority in this way are Downfall and Archipelago.

314
00:17:06,693 --> 00:17:10,974
by Caroline Hobbs tells a story about the fall of a culture

315
00:17:10,974 --> 00:17:13,254
that we create during the game that ends up

316
00:17:13,254 --> 00:17:15,995
succumbing to its fatal flaws.

317
00:17:15,995 --> 00:17:17,695
It does this by splitting authority

318
00:17:17,695 --> 00:17:21,056
over players who control the roles of the hero, the pillar,

319
00:17:21,056 --> 00:17:24,317
and the fallen, who then each push and pull each other

320
00:17:24,317 --> 00:17:27,038
by representing different elements of the society.

321
00:17:27,718 --> 00:17:30,059
So in a scene, in each scene,

322
00:17:30,059 --> 00:17:32,540
the hero tries to save the world, naturally,

323
00:17:32,540 --> 00:17:34,641
the fallen tries to corrupt it,

324
00:17:34,641 --> 00:17:36,661
and the pillar, an average person,

325
00:17:36,661 --> 00:17:39,643
tries to stifle change, maintain status quo.

326
00:17:39,643 --> 00:17:43,364
Every two scenes, roles rotate,

327
00:17:43,364 --> 00:17:46,365
and that allows each player to embody all of the roles

328
00:17:46,365 --> 00:17:47,386
over the course of the game.

329
00:17:47,386 --> 00:17:50,847
Each role also comes with certain mechanical responsibilities

330
00:17:50,847 --> 00:17:53,088
like framing scenes, which again,

331
00:17:53,088 --> 00:17:55,209
effectively carve up the GM's traditional role.

332
00:17:57,807 --> 00:18:03,244
Archipelago is another great example that experiments with narrative control through

333
00:18:03,244 --> 00:18:04,287
a few different mechanics.

334
00:18:05,654 --> 00:18:11,436
Important narrative license and environmental themes are divided among the players themselves.

335
00:18:11,436 --> 00:18:16,798
So for example, if we're playing a game in a sailing boat traversing the Pacific, one

336
00:18:16,798 --> 00:18:21,019
player may control the elements of the weather or the ship.

337
00:18:21,019 --> 00:18:26,701
And whenever uncertainty is raised about that element, you will have authority over what

338
00:18:26,701 --> 00:18:27,241
happens.

339
00:18:27,942 --> 00:18:32,984
It also intersperses that with moments of narrative surprise by employing these really

340
00:18:32,984 --> 00:18:39,468
neat things called ritual phrases that players can use to prompt one another to change things.

341
00:18:39,468 --> 00:18:44,711
So for example, you can use a card like, that might not be quite so easy to signal that

342
00:18:44,711 --> 00:18:47,212
you want to ramp up an answer and go another way.

343
00:18:49,107 --> 00:18:56,192
All of this stems from sort of a core principle that's prevalent in the story gaming design

344
00:18:56,192 --> 00:18:59,575
language that's called the SEGA principle.

345
00:18:59,575 --> 00:19:04,639
It states that when one person is the author of both the character's adversity and its

346
00:19:04,639 --> 00:19:06,940
resolution, play is not fun.

347
00:19:08,250 --> 00:19:13,192
So all of these examples give us ways to distribute that work between players

348
00:19:13,192 --> 00:19:16,473
to make sure that even when narrative authority is split,

349
00:19:16,473 --> 00:19:20,395
there isn't a player just stuck in a loop answering their own questions.

350
00:19:26,252 --> 00:19:29,514
So finally, we can ask ourselves,

351
00:19:29,514 --> 00:19:33,295
with all of these games distributing narrative control

352
00:19:33,295 --> 00:19:35,736
in interesting ways, where does that necessarily

353
00:19:35,736 --> 00:19:38,778
lie within your medium, with my medium?

354
00:19:38,778 --> 00:19:41,739
Who provides adversity, and what does that come from,

355
00:19:41,739 --> 00:19:43,400
or where does that come from in a game?

356
00:19:44,836 --> 00:19:49,461
If your default is to consider that it should come from the system the players are engaging

357
00:19:49,461 --> 00:19:51,603
with, maybe it's time to challenge that.

358
00:19:51,603 --> 00:19:56,769
You may be able to introduce more distribution and narrative authority than you think, and

359
00:19:56,769 --> 00:20:00,773
in doing so you can give players much more agency over the things that they want to explore.

360
00:20:01,474 --> 00:20:04,155
So who has control of what goes past,

361
00:20:04,155 --> 00:20:07,637
just who unfolds the next narrative beat,

362
00:20:07,637 --> 00:20:09,919
but also fundamentally what topic

363
00:20:09,919 --> 00:20:10,980
someone wants to engage with.

364
00:20:10,980 --> 00:20:16,303
And it really ensures that players can investigate

365
00:20:16,303 --> 00:20:18,204
the themes that they enthusiastically want to.

366
00:20:18,204 --> 00:20:20,586
These choices inform the themes

367
00:20:20,586 --> 00:20:23,207
that ultimately define the narrative,

368
00:20:23,207 --> 00:20:25,048
so that it's not tied to the fiat

369
00:20:25,048 --> 00:20:26,850
of one single creative authority.

370
00:20:28,403 --> 00:20:31,424
So, I offer you this question.

371
00:20:31,424 --> 00:20:32,445
Who is in charge here?

372
00:20:32,445 --> 00:20:35,326
Another concept that I'd like to offer is something called the fruitful void, which

373
00:20:35,326 --> 00:20:40,748
has really helped me structure thoughts around narratives in the past.

374
00:20:40,748 --> 00:20:53,194
It has its origins from some of the community discussion boards in the 90s and has since

375
00:20:53,194 --> 00:20:56,775
become entrenched in the design language across the whole discipline.

376
00:21:00,472 --> 00:21:06,096
Dogs in the Vineyard, I'm giving you lots of good recs today, is a game by Vincent Baker

377
00:21:06,096 --> 00:21:09,900
based on a West that never quite was.

378
00:21:09,900 --> 00:21:14,824
It's a jams game and players are God's watchdogs, or just dogs.

379
00:21:14,824 --> 00:21:19,748
And as part of their duties, they travel from city to city delivering the mail, helping

380
00:21:19,748 --> 00:21:23,411
out with community functions and also, of course, enforcing judgments of the true faith

381
00:21:23,411 --> 00:21:25,073
of the king of life, as you do.

382
00:21:26,153 --> 00:21:31,579
So Vincent Baker once published this image on his blog,

383
00:21:31,579 --> 00:21:34,822
and all of the arrows are mechanics in the game.

384
00:21:34,822 --> 00:21:37,785
You don't need to know what they represent specifically in the game,

385
00:21:37,785 --> 00:21:40,968
but just to know that he stated that what was in the whirlwind itself

386
00:21:40,968 --> 00:21:43,190
was what the game was actually about,

387
00:21:43,190 --> 00:21:45,432
what those mechanics are pointing towards.

388
00:21:49,461 --> 00:21:55,767
This concept of the real meat in your game being about what isn't mechanized has been

389
00:21:55,767 --> 00:21:56,969
formalized many times.

390
00:21:56,969 --> 00:22:04,837
So for example, My Life with Master, this is a game about roleplaying as minions of

391
00:22:04,837 --> 00:22:07,880
this powerful master or mistress.

392
00:22:07,880 --> 00:22:11,864
It mechanized stats like wariness and self-loathing.

393
00:22:12,485 --> 00:22:14,832
but it never talks about defiance,

394
00:22:14,832 --> 00:22:17,239
even though that's what all the mechanics in the game

395
00:22:17,239 --> 00:22:19,506
are hurling at the player to think about.

396
00:22:21,372 --> 00:22:25,394
So similarly, part of Emily Kierboss' romance trilogy,

397
00:22:25,394 --> 00:22:29,256
Breaking the Ice, is a great, great game for two people

398
00:22:29,256 --> 00:22:31,557
who play characters over the course of three dates,

399
00:22:31,557 --> 00:22:33,238
hopefully to find love.

400
00:22:33,238 --> 00:22:36,539
And the game mechanizes things like attraction

401
00:22:36,539 --> 00:22:40,801
and compatibility, but as Emily says right here,

402
00:22:40,801 --> 00:22:43,682
thinking about mechanizing the moment of falling in love

403
00:22:43,682 --> 00:22:44,343
is just silly.

404
00:22:44,343 --> 00:22:48,104
So she described the fruitful void of that game

405
00:22:48,104 --> 00:22:49,825
as being love and vulnerability.

406
00:22:53,443 --> 00:22:57,465
So when designing the mechanics around the emotional impact

407
00:22:57,465 --> 00:23:00,666
and narrative arc that you want the players to have,

408
00:23:00,666 --> 00:23:03,688
consider what it is and isn't,

409
00:23:03,688 --> 00:23:06,549
and what is explicitly mechanized.

410
00:23:06,549 --> 00:23:09,050
So what's nailed down and what are the mechanics

411
00:23:09,050 --> 00:23:11,851
swirling around and throwing into question?

412
00:23:11,851 --> 00:23:15,092
If you have an explicit system that measures the morality,

413
00:23:15,092 --> 00:23:16,853
say, of the player's actions,

414
00:23:16,853 --> 00:23:19,034
how would that change the player's reaction to it?

415
00:23:20,315 --> 00:23:25,965
And if your system really is about morality, how can you add force behind those pinwheels

416
00:23:25,965 --> 00:23:27,007
causing it to twist and turn?

417
00:23:31,493 --> 00:23:33,415
Now I offer you a final concept.

418
00:23:33,415 --> 00:23:36,558
Artifacts of play.

419
00:23:36,558 --> 00:23:38,620
So these are side products of play

420
00:23:38,620 --> 00:23:40,561
that exist in the physical world,

421
00:23:40,561 --> 00:23:42,863
the one that we occupy as humans.

422
00:23:42,863 --> 00:23:46,906
These can really help increase the emotional resonance

423
00:23:46,906 --> 00:23:49,849
of a narrative that the players experience in game

424
00:23:49,849 --> 00:23:52,471
by bridging the physical world that they live in

425
00:23:52,471 --> 00:23:55,314
and then the imaginary one that they occupy in play.

426
00:23:55,314 --> 00:23:57,656
So these artifacts live past the game.

427
00:23:59,212 --> 00:24:01,334
Familiar cases of this in the digital context

428
00:24:01,334 --> 00:24:04,095
may be stuff like automatically generated tweets

429
00:24:04,095 --> 00:24:07,557
based on cute words that are used in word games

430
00:24:07,557 --> 00:24:10,058
that are funny even if you're not actively playing the game

431
00:24:10,058 --> 00:24:12,279
or some of the pictures that you could take

432
00:24:12,279 --> 00:24:14,000
and keep in Firewatch.

433
00:24:14,000 --> 00:24:16,662
So story games have been experimenting

434
00:24:16,662 --> 00:24:19,623
with these for a while and they can pack a good punch.

435
00:24:21,987 --> 00:24:26,715
One example is from The Quiet Year by Avery Alder.

436
00:24:26,715 --> 00:24:30,341
So Avery Alder's game about telling the story

437
00:24:30,341 --> 00:24:33,687
of a single quiet year experienced by a community

438
00:24:33,687 --> 00:24:35,310
before the jackals return.

439
00:24:36,317 --> 00:24:39,377
So every turn the active player turns over a card,

440
00:24:39,377 --> 00:24:43,098
which then asks them to answer one of two questions

441
00:24:43,098 --> 00:24:45,098
about what is happening to the community.

442
00:24:45,098 --> 00:24:46,939
They then get to take an action of their choice

443
00:24:46,939 --> 00:24:50,479
to help address the challenges that the community is facing.

444
00:24:50,479 --> 00:24:54,040
So a completely brilliant part about this game

445
00:24:54,040 --> 00:24:57,121
is how these changes are all reflected on a map

446
00:24:57,121 --> 00:24:58,981
that the players are collaboratively drawing

447
00:24:58,981 --> 00:25:00,341
and creating during play.

448
00:25:00,341 --> 00:25:01,782
So you create the map.

449
00:25:01,782 --> 00:25:04,462
It's a game of cartography and storytelling.

450
00:25:05,803 --> 00:25:09,486
This map exists in the physical space

451
00:25:09,486 --> 00:25:13,270
and that the players occupy as human beings

452
00:25:13,270 --> 00:25:15,592
so that you can touch it, you can fold it,

453
00:25:15,592 --> 00:25:17,594
doodle on it, interact with it.

454
00:25:17,594 --> 00:25:19,416
But having this physical artifact

455
00:25:19,416 --> 00:25:23,540
really bridges the worlds, the one within the narrative

456
00:25:23,540 --> 00:25:25,902
and the one that the players live in as humans.

457
00:25:25,902 --> 00:25:27,343
It becomes also a living record

458
00:25:27,343 --> 00:25:30,086
of this particular instance of the game.

459
00:25:32,265 --> 00:25:37,011
For a second example, I offer one of our games

460
00:25:37,011 --> 00:25:40,055
to reinforce that artifacts don't necessarily

461
00:25:40,055 --> 00:25:42,618
have to be physical.

462
00:25:42,618 --> 00:25:46,803
In dialect, players tell the story of an isolated community

463
00:25:46,803 --> 00:25:50,688
by building their language over the course of play.

464
00:25:50,688 --> 00:25:51,169
I will explain.

465
00:25:53,871 --> 00:26:02,734
In every turn of dialect, players add to the story of the isolation while simultaneously modifying the language.

466
00:26:02,734 --> 00:26:09,116
So in each turn, players define new words for their community and start using them as they roleplay members of the isolation.

467
00:26:09,856 --> 00:26:15,520
that means that they gain fluency in their own dialect as the game progresses.

468
00:26:15,520 --> 00:26:19,883
So things happen to the community, language shifts, and becomes more layered to reflect it.

469
00:26:19,883 --> 00:26:25,807
And so in doing so, players discover the essence of these people that they're creating together,

470
00:26:25,807 --> 00:26:30,891
and the dialect they make becomes a language map, say, of what has happened to them.

471
00:26:32,654 --> 00:26:39,357
The language that you create in dialect is definitely an artifact of play.

472
00:26:39,357 --> 00:26:44,879
But why does this enhance the narrative experience the game tells about the language itself?

473
00:26:44,879 --> 00:26:50,101
So every game centers upon the entire life cycle of the language.

474
00:26:50,101 --> 00:26:53,522
It starts from its birth all the way to its eventual demise.

475
00:26:53,522 --> 00:26:58,845
The story experienced in the narrative is actually paralleled by the experience that

476
00:26:58,845 --> 00:27:00,405
the players have at the table.

477
00:27:01,661 --> 00:27:05,984
So the language that they're speaking together is born as the language of the isolation.

478
00:27:05,984 --> 00:27:11,647
But when the isolation's language is lost, or you stop playing this game, the players

479
00:27:11,647 --> 00:27:16,550
find themselves also as the sole speakers of this dialect that they just created.

480
00:27:16,550 --> 00:27:18,171
So they too will go through this process.

481
00:27:19,508 --> 00:27:22,131
It's by blurring the line between what is real

482
00:27:22,131 --> 00:27:25,373
and what exists in the game, in this case the language,

483
00:27:25,373 --> 00:27:28,036
that we can mirror an experience the characters have,

484
00:27:28,036 --> 00:27:29,517
the death of their language,

485
00:27:29,517 --> 00:27:31,799
with one, the player's experience,

486
00:27:31,799 --> 00:27:34,541
abruptly losing their language that they've been speaking in

487
00:27:34,541 --> 00:27:35,942
for the last three hours.

488
00:27:35,942 --> 00:27:39,065
That is a powerful connection to be left with.

489
00:27:44,470 --> 00:27:49,673
So I ask, what can you build during play that lasts beyond the game?

490
00:27:49,673 --> 00:27:54,596
Consider whether or not the experience that your players have as characters can be mirrored

491
00:27:54,596 --> 00:27:57,578
as a real experience that your players have as humans.

492
00:27:57,578 --> 00:28:00,620
Can you share elements between the two?

493
00:28:00,620 --> 00:28:04,642
And if so, you may find that the narrative hits home and packs a punch at a deeper and

494
00:28:04,642 --> 00:28:05,403
much more genuine level.

495
00:28:09,155 --> 00:28:12,295
Our time here is short, and so I leave you

496
00:28:12,295 --> 00:28:15,796
with these concepts and questions,

497
00:28:15,796 --> 00:28:20,477
a small slice of the ground that indie RPGs are breaking.

498
00:28:20,477 --> 00:28:23,538
There's lots that narrative design across all mediums

499
00:28:23,538 --> 00:28:25,859
can learn from this incredible game space

500
00:28:25,859 --> 00:28:28,359
in order to tell deeper and more resonating stories.

501
00:28:28,359 --> 00:28:32,720
The only thing left to do is to go out there and play them.

502
00:28:32,720 --> 00:28:32,860
